text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Indian Sign Language%0a%0a:Author: nithyas%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAwareness of ISL and Shortcomings of Indian Sign Language Education%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI began investigating ISL after wondering whether the wide variation in spoken Indian languages was reflected in its sign languages (i.e., if there were sign languages originating from each region as there are spoken languages corresponding to each region). The sign language is more or less standardized throughout the country, although according to Wikipedia each region has its own dialect. The dialects listed include Bangalore-Madras (South), Bombay (West), Kolkata (East), and Delhi (North), among others. The Indian Sign Language also appears to be closely related to Pakistani Sign Language and Nepalese Sign Language.%0a%0aUnfortunately, there are not many opportunities for deaf/mute children in India to learn ISL. The teaching practices for these students tends to be more "oralist," meaning that instead of teaching the sign language, schools tend to teach deaf and mute children how to read lips and understand spoken language that way. ISL also lacks strong government support - according to one government website, there are about 5 million deaf people in the country, but ISL is not officially taught in deaf schools and it has "less than 300 certified interpreters." Additionally, many parents of these children do not know the resources available to help educate their child in ISL. Luckily, there has been an effort in recent years to help "promote and develop sign language and teaching and training of interpreters." This began with the opening of the Indian Sign Language Research and Training Center in New Delhi in 2015.%0a%0aSources:%0ahttp://www.islrtc.nic.in/history-0%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indo-Pakistani_Sign_Language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210507-162418-180460#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Developing an ISL Dictionary  %0a-> - roochis%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aRecently, they've approved the development of India's first Sign Language Dictionary. When its completed, the dictionary will translate between English and Hindi signs. It dictionary aims to include almost 10,000 signs in a variety of  (and their English translation).  This is a very daunting task. As you said in your article, India is incredibly linguistically diverse, and as a result, there are many regional dialects of ISL. Additionally, unlike ASL, ISL isn't written. Which adds an additional layer of challenge. The dictionary will comprise of images of ISL signs nd images of their corresponding English signs. Hopefully, this dictionary can standardize ISL. This, in turn, can foster the development of ISL classes in schools. %0a%0ahttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-39101899  %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210507-162418-180460#%0a#foxbegin 210509-031207-221180#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!ISL as an official language of India %0a-> - AnanyaV%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn recent years, there have been pushes to declare ISL an official language in India, with a petition filed by the National Association of the Deaf in India. In May 2020, Bollywood actor Ranveer Singh released a music video for the rapper-poet Spitfire called 'Vartalap', which was signed in ISL.%0a%0ahttps://theprint.in/opinion/indian-sign-language-should-be-declared-official-language-but-only-taught-by-deaf-trainers/432627/%0a%0ahttps://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/ranveer-singh-promotes-inclusivity-wants-indian-sign-language-to-be-declared-as-the-23rd-official-language/articleshow/75916018.cms%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-031207-221180#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
